Visualizing high dimensional data

Cory Whitney, Eduardo Fernandez

2019-03-28

Dealing with large data sets can sometimes be confusing. Particularly if you are working in spreadsheets. Visualization is a powerful too to help get an overview of findings and reporting patterns and differences in data. Aims objectives and hypotheses should, of course, be determined before any data is collected.

Here we demonstrate approaches to using visualization for several types of high dimensional data using number of useful plotting functions from ggplot2, plyr, dplyr and tidyverse in teh R programming language.

Radial bar plots

Create a data set for radial plots with a factor variable

DF <- data.frame(variable = as.factor(1:10),
                 value = sample(10, replace = TRUE))
head(DF)
##   variable value
## 1        1     7
## 2        2     9
## 3        3     2
## 4        4     5
## 5        5     5
## 6        6     6

Create a function to compute standard error of mean to reprsent some of the uncertainty in the data

se <- function(x) sqrt(var(x)/length(x)) 
set.seed(9876)

Radial plot with a factor variable

ggplot(DF, aes(variable, value, fill = variable)) +
  geom_bar(width = 1, stat = "identity", color = "white") +
  geom_errorbar(aes(ymin = value - se(DF$value), 
                    ymax = value + se(DF$value), 
                    color = variable), 
                width = .2) + 
  scale_y_continuous(breaks = 0:nlevels(DF$variable)) +
  theme_minimal() +
  coord_polar()

Radial plots with three factor variables

multi_plot <- ggplot(DF2, aes(variable, value, fill = variable)) +
  geom_bar(width = 1, stat = "identity", color = "white") +
  geom_errorbar(aes(ymin = value - se(DF2$value),

Rows as names and columns as variables variable2

# Rows are name and columns are variable2
multi_plot + facet_grid(name ~ variable2)

Radial box plots

Radial box plot with a data set and grid with four factor variables and one continuous.

multi_plot <- ggplot(data = DF3, aes(x=variable, y=value, fill=variable)) +
  geom_boxplot() +
  scale_y_continuous(breaks = 0:nlevels(DF3$variable)) +
  theme_minimal() +
  coord_polar()
multi_plot

Radial box plot with rows as names and columns as variables variable2

multi_plot + facet_grid(name ~ variable2)

Sunburst plot

Create data set for a sunburst-style barplot confined to a circle

# make some fake data
DF5 <- data.frame(
  'level1'=c('a', 'a', 'a', 'a', 'b', 'b', 'c', 'c', 'c'), 
  'level2'=c('a1', 'a2', 'a3', 'a4', 'b1', 'b2', 'c1', 'c2', 'c3'), 
  'value'=c(.025, .05, .027, .005, .012, .014, .1, .03, .18))
head(DF5)
##   level1 level2 value
## 1      a     a1 0.025
## 2      a     a2 0.050
## 3      a     a3 0.027
## 4      a     a4 0.005
## 5      b     b1 0.012
## 6      b     b2 0.014

Create a sunburst-style barplot confined to a circle

ggplot(DF5, aes(y=value)) +
  geom_bar(aes(fill=level1, x=0), width=.5, stat='identity') + 
  geom_bar(aes(fill=level2, x=.25), width=.25, stat='identity') + 
  coord_polar(theta='y') + 
  theme_minimal()

Spider plot

Create a function to obtain straight lines

coord_radar <- 
  function(theta='x', start=0, direction=1){
    # input parameter sanity check
    match.arg(theta, c('x','y'))
    
    ggproto(
      NULL, CoordPolar, 
      theta=theta, r=ifelse(theta=='x','y','x'),
      start=start, direction=sign(direction),
      is_linear=function() TRUE)
  }

Create a new dataset and a spider plot

factor <- c(rep("A", 16), rep("B", 16))
variable <- as.factor(c(1:16))
value <- sample(c(1:10),32,replace = T)

One way to close the plot is to add an extra level of variable which needs the same value as level 1. Both factors (A and B) need this correction.

value[16] <- value[1]
value[32] <- value[17]  
data <- data.frame(factor = factor, variable = variable, value = value)

With ggplot

ggplot(data, aes(as.numeric(data$variable),value)) + coord_radar() +
  geom_path() + scale_x_continuous(breaks = c(1:15)) +
  labs(x = "variable") + facet_wrap(.~ factor) + theme_minimal()

Bubble plot of continuous data

Create data which is all continuous

DF6 <- data.frame(replicate(4,sample(1:200,1000,rep=TRUE)))
addme <- data.frame(replicate(1,sample(0:1,1000,rep=TRUE)))
DF6 <- cbind(DF6,addme)

Add column names

colnames(DF6) <- c("var1","var2","var3","var4","var5")

Create the bubble plot using ggplot

ggplot(DF6, aes(x=var1, y=var2, fill=var3, color=var4, size=var5)) +
  geom_point(shape=21) +
  #scale_color_gradient(low="grey", high="black") +
  #scale_color_gradientn(colours = rainbow(3))+
  scale_size_continuous(range=c(1,12))+ 
  scale_fill_gradient(low="grey", high="black")

Bubble plot of and categorical data

Here we use var3 and var4 as quantiles to apply to plot area

DF6$var4.cat <- cut(DF6$var4, quantile(DF6$var4, (0:5)/5), include.lowest=T)
DF6$var3.cat <- cut(DF6$var3, quantile(DF6$var3, (0:5)/5), include.lowest=T)

Plot continuous and categorical data using facet_grid

ggplot(DF6, aes(x=var1, y=var2, fill=var4, color=var3, size=var5^2)) +
  geom_point(shape=21) +
  scale_color_gradient(low="red", high="green") +
  scale_size_continuous(range=c(1,12)) +
  facet_grid(var3.cat ~ var4.cat)
